# Assignment 6 - vants

## Project Links

- Live Demo: https://biwendong.github.io/CS4300-Graphics_Simulation_Aesthetics/A6/

## Aesthetic Intent
Although the behavior of individual Langton’s Ants is very simple, the system as a whole can generate complex patterns. Building on this foundation, I introduced multiple ant types, transforming the system from one governed by a single rule into one driven by the interaction of different rules. I also employed a limited color palette to distinguish between different ant types and the trails they leave behind. For example, classic ants use cyan trails, reverse ants use purple, and builder ants use orange.

## Technical Exploration
This project uses WebGPU to store grid data in the GPU’s storage buffer. The position, direction, and type of each ant are also stored independently, allowing for the parallel updating of multiple ants’ behaviors on the GPU. Building on the basic Langton’s Ant rules, I have implemented three distinct behavioral patterns. Classic ants turn right at empty cells and leave a trail, while turning left at existing trails and clearing them. Reverse ants completely reverse this rule, whereas builder ants do not turn when encountering an existing trail but instead continue forward and leave a trail.
